<h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
  If a basic criminal record check is requested
</h3>

<p class="govuk-body">
  When a caution or conviction is spent you do not need to tell people about it, or the offence that led to it, if
  they’re requesting a
  <a class="govuk-link" rel="external" target="_blank" href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/telling-people-about-your-criminal-record#basic-dbs-checks">basic
    criminal record check</a>.
</p>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
  If a standard or enhanced criminal record check is requested
</h3>

<p class="govuk-body">
  You will need to tell people about spent cautions or convictions if they’re requesting a
  <a class="govuk-link" rel="external" target="_blank" href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/telling-people-about-your-criminal-record#standard-dbs">standard
    or enhanced criminal
    record check</a>.
</p>

<div class="govuk-inset-text">
  Some spent cautions and convictions are
  <a class="govuk-link" rel="external" target="_blank" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dbs-filtering-guidance">’protected’
    or ‘filtered’</a> and will not show up on a standard or enhanced
  criminal record check.
</div>

<h3 class="govuk-heading-s">
  If you have more than one caution or conviction
</h3>

<p class="govuk-body">
  The result you've been given might be incorrect if you have other convictions.
</p>

<p class="govuk-body">
  You should get professional or legal advice if you:
</p>

<ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
  <li>got another conviction during a rehabilitation period</li>
  <li>are applying for certain sensitive jobs, such as a policeman or lawyer</li>
</ul>
